```c++
#include <string>
#include <sstream>
#include <algorithm>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
  std::ostringstream html;

  // Convert markdown headers to HTML headers
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), '#', '<h1>');
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), '#', '</h1>');

  // Convert markdown lists to HTML lists
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), '-', '<li>');
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), '-', '</li>');

  // Convert markdown links to HTML links
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), '(', '<a href="');
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), ')', '">');

  // Convert markdown images to HTML images
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), '!', '<img src="');
  std::replace(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), '!', '" />');

  html << markdown;

  return html.str();
}
```

In this implementation, we use the replace function to search for specific characters in the input string and replace them with corresponding HTML tags. For example, we replace '#' with '<h1>' and '</h1>' to convert markdown headers to HTML headers. Similarly, we replace '-' with '<li>' and '</li>' to convert markdown lists to HTML lists, and so on.

The function takes a const reference to a std::string as input, which allows it to modify the input string without creating a new copy of the string. The function then uses an ostringstream (which is essentially a stream that writes to a string) to build the output HTML string. Finally, it returns the output HTML string as a std::string.

